{#- CLEANUP VS CATCH-UP — prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="pcl-cleanup-vs-catchup">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Cleanup vs. catch-up</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">Two different problems, two ranges.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p><strong>Cleanup ($1,500&ndash;$15,000+)</strong> fixes books that exist but are wrong &mdash; reconciliations that don&rsquo;t tie, miscategorized history, an undeposited-funds pileup, a chart of accounts that needs rebuilding, a corrupted or restructured file. The work is correction: finding the errors and proving the fix. The full QuickBooks cleanup service, with its three tiers, lives on the <a href="/quickbooks/cleanup/">QuickBooks cleanup</a> page; the bookkeeping-side detail is on <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/cleanup-bookkeeping/">cleanup bookkeeping</a>.</p>
      <p><strong>Catch-up ($2,000&ndash;$20,000+)</strong> records books that were never done &mdash; months or years of transactions never entered, reconciled, or closed. The work is reconstruction: building each period from source documents, in order. The detail lives on <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/catch-up-bookkeeping/">catch-up bookkeeping</a>.</p>
      <p>Many files need both &mdash; the recent past was never recorded (catch-up) and what was recorded earlier was done wrong (cleanup). When that&rsquo;s the case, the file review scopes them as one project with one fixed fee, sequenced so the foundation is sound before the backlog is built on top of it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

